WEBVTT

00:01.002 --> 00:05.005
â™ªâ™ª [Overture]

05:31.165 --> 05:32.165
[Bells Pealing]

05:32.166 --> 05:35.168
[Bells Pealing]

05:44.721 --> 05:47.723
[Bell Tolling]

08:31.804 --> 08:34.806
[Sobbing Quietly]

08:48.362 --> 08:51.364
[Bells Pealing]

09:24.482 --> 09:26.733
Mr. Frank.

09:26.817 --> 09:28.818
Mr. Frank?

09:33.950 --> 09:35.951
Kraler?

09:39.747 --> 09:42.165
[Mr. Frank]
Mr. Kraler.

09:42.250 --> 09:44.251
Miep.

09:47.088 --> 09:49.005
My good friends.

09:49.090 --> 09:51.007
Oh, it-

09:51.092 --> 09:54.344
it is so good
to see you home.

09:54.428 --> 09:56.429
We had heard nothing.

09:59.433 --> 10:01.685
I'm alone.

10:01.769 --> 10:04.688
You must
come home
with us...

10:04.772 --> 10:06.773
and rest now.

10:06.899 --> 10:11.403
You must stay with us.
No, Miep. I can't
stay in Amsterdam.

10:12.697 --> 10:16.491
Mr. Frank,
this is your home.

10:16.575 --> 10:18.493
Amsterdam
is your home.

10:18.577 --> 10:20.996
It has too many
memories for me.

10:21.080 --> 10:22.998
Everywhere there's
something, Miep.
Everywhere.

10:23.082 --> 10:25.834
Even seeing
you and Mr. Kraler.

10:28.879 --> 10:32.299
Forgive me. I shouldn't
talk to you like this
after all that you did.

10:32.383 --> 10:34.384
We would
do it again.

10:36.387 --> 10:39.264
Everything's gone-
the book.

10:39.348 --> 10:41.266
They took
everything...

10:41.350 --> 10:43.268
except some papers.

10:43.352 --> 10:45.854
We saved
your letters
and papers.

10:51.861 --> 10:54.237
Please burn them.

10:54.322 --> 10:56.239
Burn everything.

10:56.324 --> 10:59.242
I- I...

10:59.327 --> 11:03.455
told Anne
if I got back here,
I'd find her book.

11:03.539 --> 11:07.292
Anne's diary?
It's where she left it.

11:57.968 --> 12:01.971
"The ninth of July, 1942."

12:03.808 --> 12:06.643
1942.
Is it possible, Miep?

12:06.727 --> 12:09.521
Only three years ago.

12:09.605 --> 12:13.525
"Dear Diary,
since you and I are going
to be great friends,

12:13.609 --> 12:17.028
"I will start
by telling you
all about myself.

12:17.113 --> 12:19.280
"My name is Anne Frank.

12:19.365 --> 12:21.282
"I am 13 years old.

12:21.367 --> 12:23.284
"I was born in Germany,

12:23.369 --> 12:25.286
"but since my family
is Jewish,

12:25.371 --> 12:28.790
"we emigrated to Holland
when Hitler came to power.

12:28.874 --> 12:31.793
[Mr. Frank, Anne's Voices
Overlapping]
"Things went well for us...

12:31.877 --> 12:34.796
"until the war came,
and the German occupation.

12:34.880 --> 12:37.799
"Then things got very bad
for the Jews.

12:37.883 --> 12:41.428
[Anne's Voice Only]
You could not do this,
and you could not do that.

12:41.512 --> 12:44.431
We had to wear
yellow stars.

12:44.515 --> 12:46.766
I had to turn in my bike.

12:46.851 --> 12:49.769
I couldn't go
to a Dutch school anymore.

12:49.854 --> 12:53.273
I couldn't go to the movies
or ride in an automobile,

12:53.357 --> 12:55.275
or even on a streetcar,

12:55.359 --> 12:58.111
and a million other things.

12:58.195 --> 13:02.782
But somehow we children
still managed to have fun.

13:02.867 --> 13:06.119
This morning Father
woke me at 5:00...

13:06.203 --> 13:09.622
and told me
to hurry and get dressed.

13:09.707 --> 13:12.292
We were going into hiding.

13:12.376 --> 13:15.628
I was to put on
as many clothes as I could.

13:15.713 --> 13:19.716
It would look too suspicious
if we walked along
carrying suitcases.

13:21.177 --> 13:23.720
We were going to disappear,

13:23.804 --> 13:26.473
vanish into thin air.

13:30.728 --> 13:33.730
I'm living
a great adventure.

13:41.238 --> 13:43.656
Three other people
were coming in with us.

13:43.741 --> 13:46.493
Father knew them,
but we had never met them.

13:46.577 --> 13:48.578
[Sighs]

13:58.464 --> 14:00.381
Something's
happened.

14:00.466 --> 14:02.342
They have three miles
to walk.

14:02.468 --> 14:04.886
Mother-
They've been
arrested. I know.

14:04.970 --> 14:07.514
Will you
stop that?
Mother! Father!

14:07.598 --> 14:09.891
We're here.

14:09.975 --> 14:11.976
See?

14:14.522 --> 14:16.439
Mr. Van Daan.
Hello, hello.

14:16.524 --> 14:19.609
Mrs. Van Daan. Peter.
[Chuckling]
Mr. Frank.

14:19.693 --> 14:22.612
There were too many
of the Green Police
on the streets.

14:22.696 --> 14:25.073
We had to take
the long way around.

14:25.199 --> 14:29.494
Did you introduce yourself?
My daughter Anne. My wife Edith.
Hello.

14:29.578 --> 14:31.496
Margot.
Mr. and Mrs. Van Daan.
Hello.

14:31.580 --> 14:34.499
Oh, and this is
our son Peter.

14:34.583 --> 14:39.420
So, now, please,
let us take off
some of these clothes.

14:39.505 --> 14:41.422
[Mr. Kraler]
Good morning.

14:41.507 --> 14:43.925
Hello, Mr. Kraler.
Good morning,
Mr. Kraler.

14:44.009 --> 14:46.594
Mr. Frank.
Ah, you're all here.
That is good.

14:46.679 --> 14:49.097
We had hoped to have
everything in order.

14:49.181 --> 14:51.599
Please, Mr. Kraler,
don't even think of it.

14:51.684 --> 14:54.561
After all, we'll have
plenty of leisure to arrange
everything ourselves.

14:54.687 --> 14:57.605
I brought some sandwiches
for your lunch.
Thank you, Miep.

14:57.690 --> 15:00.567
The canned goods are here,
and your stores
of dried beans and potatoes.

15:00.693 --> 15:04.112
I'll get you ration books
this afternoon.
Ration books?

15:04.196 --> 15:07.448
If they see our names
on ration books,
they'll know we're here.

15:07.533 --> 15:10.702
Don't worry.
It won't be your names
that'll be on them.

15:12.162 --> 15:14.080
[Bells Pealing]

15:14.164 --> 15:16.082
Father!
The Westertoren!

15:16.166 --> 15:18.167
Anne, no!

15:19.295 --> 15:21.713
You must never
touch a curtain.
Never.

15:21.797 --> 15:25.216
No one must ever
touch a curtain,
day or night.

15:25.301 --> 15:28.761
If someone on the streets
should look up, or someone
in those houses should see,

15:28.846 --> 15:30.680
we would be lost.

15:30.764 --> 15:33.683
Please remember,
it's not only our lives
that are at stake,

15:33.767 --> 15:35.643
but also Miep's
and Mr. Kraler's.

15:35.769 --> 15:38.605
You have but 13 minutes
to get settled.
Thank you.

15:38.689 --> 15:43.568
Miep or I will be up each day
to bring you food and news.
Come, Miep. We must go.

15:43.652 --> 15:45.653
Good-bye for now.

15:46.780 --> 15:48.990
How can we thank you?

15:50.576 --> 15:53.494
I never thought
I'd live to see the day...

15:53.579 --> 15:56.497
when a man like Mr. Frank
would have to go into hiding.

15:56.582 --> 15:58.750
When you think of the-

15:58.876 --> 16:00.793
Good-bye.
Thank you,
Mr. Kraler.

16:00.878 --> 16:02.879
Good-bye, Miep.
Good-bye.

16:07.593 --> 16:09.761
Good-bye.

16:16.060 --> 16:19.812
[Edith] Anne!
It's all right.
I have on three more.

16:19.897 --> 16:21.814
Excuse me,
Mr. Frank.

16:21.899 --> 16:24.484
What did he mean,
just 13 minutes?

16:24.568 --> 16:26.486
Before
the workmen come.

16:26.570 --> 16:29.489
Now, while the men are
in the building below,

16:29.573 --> 16:31.491
we must have
complete quiet.

16:31.575 --> 16:33.993
Every sound can be
heard down there,

16:34.078 --> 16:36.996
not only in the offices
but in the workrooms too.

16:37.081 --> 16:39.957
The men come at about 8:30,
they leave at about 5:30,

16:40.042 --> 16:43.461
so to be perfectly safe,
from 8:00 in the morning
until 6:00 in the evening...

16:43.545 --> 16:46.964
we must move about up here
only when it is
absolutely necessary,

16:47.049 --> 16:48.966
and then
in stocking feet.

16:49.051 --> 16:51.969
We must not speak
above a whisper.
We must not run any water.

16:52.054 --> 16:55.473
We cannot use the sink
or even- forgive me-
the W.C.

16:55.557 --> 16:57.934
The pipes go down
through the workrooms.

16:58.060 --> 17:01.062
No trash must ever be-
[Sirens Approach,
Wailing]

17:08.404 --> 17:10.821
[Tires Screeching]

17:10.906 --> 17:13.407
[Wailing Passes,
Fades]

17:18.622 --> 17:22.541
No trash must ever be
thrown out which might reveal
that someone is living up here.

17:22.626 --> 17:24.544
Not even
a potato peeling.

17:24.627 --> 17:27.547
We must burn everything
in this stove at night.

17:27.631 --> 17:32.218
This is the way that we must
live until it is over,
if we are to survive.

17:32.302 --> 17:34.721
Until it is over.

17:34.805 --> 17:37.724
[Chuckles]
After 6:00
we can move about.

17:37.808 --> 17:41.018
We can talk and laugh,
have our supper,
read, play games,

17:41.103 --> 17:43.020
just as we would
at home.

17:43.105 --> 17:47.525
Now I think it would be wise
if we all went to our rooms
and were settled before 8:00.

17:47.609 --> 17:49.944
Mrs. Van Daan,
you and your husband
will be upstairs.

17:50.028 --> 17:52.947
I regret that
there's no place up there
for Peter,

17:53.031 --> 17:54.949
but he'll be here,
near us.

17:55.033 --> 17:58.953
- And where am I?
- You and Margot will be in there, Annele.

17:59.037 --> 18:01.414
[Mrs. Van Daan]
Excuse me, Mr. Frank.
Yes?

18:01.540 --> 18:05.585
Where do you
and Mrs. Frank sleep?
This room is also our bedroom.

18:05.669 --> 18:07.545
Oh, no.
You take the upstairs.

18:07.671 --> 18:10.590
It's not right.
It's your place.
We'll sleep down here.

18:10.674 --> 18:13.384
I've thought this out for weeks.
It's the best arrangement.
The only arrangement.

18:13.469 --> 18:15.386
Uh, Edith?

18:15.471 --> 18:17.388
Hmm?

18:17.473 --> 18:19.390
You must have
some rest, dear.

18:19.475 --> 18:21.350
You didn't
close your eyes
last night.

18:21.477 --> 18:24.145
Please go in
the girls' room with Margot.
How about Anne?

18:24.229 --> 18:28.149
I feel fine.
I'm going to help Father.

18:28.233 --> 18:30.401
This way,
Mrs. Van Daan.

18:33.572 --> 18:35.573
Excuse me.

18:37.743 --> 18:39.702
Up here.

19:11.568 --> 19:13.569
[Sighs]

19:17.908 --> 19:20.910
[Shuffling]

19:21.954 --> 19:23.955
[Peter]
Mr. Frank.

19:24.039 --> 19:26.541
- Mr. Frank?
- Peter?

19:26.625 --> 19:30.503
- Do I still have time
to get some water for my cat?
- Have you got a cat?

19:30.587 --> 19:33.422
Go ahead, but be quick.
You only have five minutes.

19:33.507 --> 19:35.758
He couldn't live
without that cat.

19:41.682 --> 19:44.100
I didn't know
you had a cat.

19:44.184 --> 19:46.102
I love cats.

19:46.186 --> 19:48.938
What's its name?
Mouschi.

19:49.022 --> 19:51.941
What is it? Mouschi.
A him or her?

19:52.025 --> 19:54.944
It's a tom, and it
doesn't like strangers.

19:55.028 --> 19:58.030
Well, I'll have to stop
being a stranger, won't I?
Is he fixed?

19:58.115 --> 20:00.032
No.

20:00.117 --> 20:03.536
Well, you ought to
have him fixed to
keep him from fighting.

20:03.620 --> 20:05.913
What a nice cat.

20:08.000 --> 20:09.917
Where do you
go to school?

20:10.002 --> 20:11.919
Jewish Secondary.

20:12.004 --> 20:13.921
That's where
Margot and I go.

20:14.006 --> 20:15.923
Yeah, I know.

20:16.008 --> 20:17.925
I've never
seen you around.

20:18.010 --> 20:19.927
I used to see you
sometimes.

20:20.012 --> 20:21.929
You did?

20:22.014 --> 20:24.932
But why didn't you
ever come over?

20:25.017 --> 20:27.894
Oh, I don't know.
I'm sort of a lone wolf.

20:27.978 --> 20:30.187
Can't be
a lone wolf here.

20:32.900 --> 20:36.986
Wonder what our friends
will say when
we don't show up today?

20:37.070 --> 20:38.905
I had a date
with Sanne.

20:38.989 --> 20:40.865
Do you know
Sanne de Vries?

20:40.991 --> 20:43.910
No.
Sanne's
my best friend.

20:43.994 --> 20:46.746
She's thin like me.

20:46.830 --> 20:50.541
They always yell at us,
"Anne and Sanne,
the skinny bananas."

20:52.628 --> 20:54.837
You took off
your star.

20:55.839 --> 20:57.757
That's right.

20:57.841 --> 21:01.677
You can't do that.
They'll arrest you if you
go out without your star.

21:01.762 --> 21:03.679
Who's going out?

21:03.764 --> 21:05.681
[Grunts]

21:05.766 --> 21:07.642
Help me.

21:07.768 --> 21:09.727
I'm helping.
[Groans]

21:11.480 --> 21:14.523
- What are you going to do with it?
- Burn it.

21:14.608 --> 21:17.610
That's funny.
I don't think I could burn mine.

21:17.694 --> 21:19.612
I don't know why.

21:19.696 --> 21:23.199
You couldn't?
Something they make you wear
so they can kick you around?

21:23.283 --> 21:25.201
I know.

21:25.285 --> 21:29.914
But, after all,
it is the Star of David, isn't it?

21:31.041 --> 21:33.376
Annele?
It's almost 8:00.

21:35.879 --> 21:39.256
Don't you want to come
and sit with us, Peter?
It's going to be a long day.

21:39.341 --> 21:41.384
No, thanks.
This is fine.

21:41.468 --> 21:44.470
You won't forget
to take off your shoes,
will you?

21:47.057 --> 21:49.475
Peter.

21:49.559 --> 21:52.061
It's nice
to have you with us.

21:53.355 --> 21:55.356
Yes, Mr. Frank.

21:57.526 --> 21:59.527
See you later.

22:01.196 --> 22:05.199
Do you know he went to
the same school that-
[Bells Pealing]

22:12.833 --> 22:16.419
[Bell Tolling 8:00]

22:41.111 --> 22:44.196
[Anne Narrating]
It's comforting to think that
Mr. Kraler and his secretary...

22:44.281 --> 22:47.366
are down there below us
in the office.

22:47.451 --> 22:49.368
Our protectors,
we call them.

22:49.453 --> 22:51.370
[Typing]

22:51.455 --> 22:54.874
I asked Father
what would happen to them
if anyone found out...

22:54.958 --> 22:56.876
they were hiding us.

22:56.960 --> 23:01.213
Father said they would suffer
the same fate that we would.

23:01.298 --> 23:03.549
[Machinery Droning]

23:03.633 --> 23:06.093
We are over
an old spice factory.

23:06.178 --> 23:09.513
You can smell the spices
all through the building.

23:20.776 --> 23:23.861
[Crowd Shouting In Unison]
Sieg heil! Sieg heil!

23:23.945 --> 23:27.031
Sieg heil! Sieg heil!

23:27.115 --> 23:30.326
Sieg heil! Sieg heil!

23:30.410 --> 23:33.496
Sieg heil! Sieg heil!

23:33.580 --> 23:36.290
Sieg heil! Sieg heil!

23:36.374 --> 23:38.375
[Shouting Fades]

24:02.025 --> 24:05.027
[Bell Tolling]

24:13.662 --> 24:16.664
[Bell Continues Tolling]

24:32.514 --> 24:35.516
[Bell Continues Tolling]

24:43.859 --> 24:46.360
[Tolling Stops]

25:01.251 --> 25:05.254
[Footsteps Marching,
Faint]

25:12.596 --> 25:15.598
[Boat Horn Blowing]

26:02.979 --> 26:07.399
I read A Tale of Two Cities
through in that first day.

26:09.152 --> 26:12.488
"It is a far,
far better thing I do...

26:12.572 --> 26:15.115
"than I have ever done.

26:15.200 --> 26:19.119
"It is a far, far better
rest that I go to...

26:19.204 --> 26:22.039
"than I have ever known.

26:23.166 --> 26:25.084
The end."

26:25.168 --> 26:28.712
It was the saddest book
I ever read.

26:46.940 --> 26:49.942
[Footsteps Approaching]

27:04.332 --> 27:06.333
[Knocking]

27:08.712 --> 27:11.380
It is us,
Miep and Kraler.

27:16.052 --> 27:18.304
[Door Opening]

27:18.388 --> 27:20.806
[Mr. Frank]
Good evening, Mr. Kraler.
Good evening, Miep.

27:20.890 --> 27:22.766
[Whispering]

27:22.892 --> 27:24.810
Evening, Annele.
Hello. Hello.

27:24.894 --> 27:26.603
Hello.

27:26.730 --> 27:28.605
Oh, Mr. Frank.
Yes?

27:28.732 --> 27:30.607
This is the box
you asked for.
Thank you.

27:30.734 --> 27:33.652
Good evening, Mr. Kraler.
My dear friends,
you are so quiet up here.

27:33.737 --> 27:35.738
I thought
you'd gone out
for a walk.

27:35.822 --> 27:38.574
[Anne]
Can you imagine me?
I didn't talk.

27:38.658 --> 27:42.745
I hardly moved for
one whole day. I wish they
could hear that at school.

27:42.829 --> 27:44.747
- [Yowling]
- Mouschi! Mouschi!

27:44.831 --> 27:47.082
- Peter!
- [Continues Yowling]

27:47.167 --> 27:49.460
Mouschi!

27:49.544 --> 27:51.587
[Continues Yowling]

27:51.713 --> 27:54.882
Shh!
Shh. Annele.

27:54.966 --> 27:57.343
Annele!
Peter,
I'm warning you.

27:57.427 --> 28:00.429
[Mr. Frank]
Please, quiet.
Margot. Margot!

28:01.639 --> 28:04.391
What are these?
You don't have to
whisper.

28:05.894 --> 28:07.811
[Mr. Van Daan Mutters,
Indistinct]

28:07.896 --> 28:09.855
[Meows]

28:13.568 --> 28:15.486
Oh, there you are.

28:15.570 --> 28:17.571
It's such a nice cat.

28:31.836 --> 28:33.921
[Peter]
Thank you.

28:34.005 --> 28:36.006
You're welcome.

28:38.635 --> 28:40.886
Annele.
There's a box there.

28:40.970 --> 28:42.971
Will you open it,
please?

28:44.265 --> 28:47.184
You know how I'm going
to think of it here?

28:47.268 --> 28:51.063
As a boardinghouse.
A very peculiar
boardinghouse.

28:51.147 --> 28:53.899
[Gasps]
Father, my film stars!

28:53.983 --> 28:57.152
I was wondering
where they were.

28:59.197 --> 29:03.158
And Queen Wilhelmina.
How wonderful.

29:03.243 --> 29:05.160
There's
something more.

29:05.245 --> 29:07.246
Go on.
Look further.

29:18.675 --> 29:21.260
A diary.

29:21.344 --> 29:24.012
I've never had a diary,

29:24.097 --> 29:27.015
and I've always wanted one.

29:27.100 --> 29:29.518
Ohh.
[Sighs]

29:29.602 --> 29:31.520
A pencil?

29:31.604 --> 29:33.647
I'm going downstairs
to get a pencil.

29:33.773 --> 29:36.150
Anne, no.
But there's nobody
down there now.

29:36.276 --> 29:39.403
It doesn't matter.
Don't ever go
beyond that door.
Ever?

29:39.487 --> 29:42.489
Never.
I'm sorry, Anne.
It isn't safe.

29:47.078 --> 29:49.663
I see.
It'll be hard.
I know that.

29:49.747 --> 29:51.665
But always remember this,
Anneke:

29:51.749 --> 29:55.669
there are no walls, no locks,
no bolts that anyone
can put on your mind.

29:55.753 --> 29:58.672
As a matter of fact,
just between us, Annele,

29:58.756 --> 30:00.674
being here has
certain advantages
for you.

30:00.758 --> 30:04.678
For instance, remember that
battle you had with your mother
on the subject of overshoes?

30:04.762 --> 30:07.306
You said you'd rather die
than wear overshoes.

30:07.390 --> 30:09.308
Remember?
[Chuckling]
Well, what happened?

30:09.392 --> 30:12.311
In the end,
you had to wear them.

30:12.395 --> 30:15.314
Now, for as long
as we are here you won't
have to wear overshoes.

30:15.398 --> 30:17.316
Isn't that good?

30:17.400 --> 30:19.318
And the piano?

30:19.402 --> 30:22.321
You won't have to
practice on the piano.

30:22.405 --> 30:26.408
I tell you, this is going
to be a fine life for you.
[Chuckling]

30:50.016 --> 30:54.436
[Anne Narrating]
It's an odd idea for someone
like me to keep a diary.

30:54.521 --> 30:57.773
Not only because
I have never done so before,

30:57.857 --> 31:02.778
but because it seems to me
that neither I, nor for
that matter anyone else,

31:02.862 --> 31:08.492
will be interested
in the unbosomings
of a 13-year-old schoolgirl.

31:08.576 --> 31:12.496
Still,
what does that matter?

31:12.580 --> 31:14.706
I want to write.

31:14.791 --> 31:16.792
But more than that,

31:16.876 --> 31:19.795
I want to bring out
all kinds of things...

31:19.879 --> 31:22.881
that lie buried
deep in my heart.

31:24.175 --> 31:27.094
First of all, I expect
I should be describing...

31:27.178 --> 31:30.055
what it's like
to go into hiding.

31:30.181 --> 31:33.183
[Birds Calling]
But I don't really
know yet myself.

31:34.644 --> 31:38.897
I only know it's funny
never to be able
to go outdoors,

31:38.982 --> 31:40.899
never to breathe
fresh air,

31:40.984 --> 31:42.901
[Shouting, Chattering]

31:42.986 --> 31:45.487
never to run
and shout and jump.

31:51.661 --> 31:56.248
Wednesday,
the 23rd of September, 1942.

31:56.332 --> 31:58.917
The news of the war is good.

31:59.002 --> 32:01.712
Stalingrad
is still holding out.

32:01.796 --> 32:05.841
The Russian offensive continues
in the Moscow area.

32:17.395 --> 32:19.771
It's safe now.
The last workman has left.
Whee!

32:19.897 --> 32:22.482
Anne!
I'm first
for the W.C.

32:23.901 --> 32:26.111
It's 6:00, Margot.
School is over.

32:26.195 --> 32:28.113
Where are
my shoes?

32:28.197 --> 32:30.782
â™ªâ™ª [Humming]

32:30.867 --> 32:33.535
Have you seen my shoes?

32:33.620 --> 32:36.705
- What shoes?
- You're gonna be sorry.

32:36.789 --> 32:38.749
- I am?
- Anne dear.

32:38.875 --> 32:41.335
[Peter]
Wait till I get you.
I'm waiting.

32:45.298 --> 32:47.257
Stop! Peter. Ouch!

32:47.342 --> 32:48.884
Anne! Peter!

32:50.386 --> 32:52.387
[Shoes Land On Floor]

32:57.185 --> 32:59.102
Hey,
where are you going?

32:59.187 --> 33:01.104
Going to give Mouschi
his dinner.

33:01.189 --> 33:03.106
Peter!

33:03.191 --> 33:06.610
Anne dear, I think
you shouldn't play
like that with Peter.

33:06.694 --> 33:08.612
It's not dignified.

33:08.696 --> 33:11.615
Who wants to be dignified?
I don't want to be dignified.

33:11.699 --> 33:15.327
You complain that I don't
treat you like a grown-up,
but when I do you resent it.

33:15.411 --> 33:17.412
I only want
some fun.

33:18.623 --> 33:22.125
I don't know
what's the matter
with that boy.

33:26.047 --> 33:29.299
Give him a little time.
He isn't used to girls.

33:29.384 --> 33:31.635
Time?
Isn't two months time?

33:31.719 --> 33:33.637
[Chuckles]
I could cry.

33:33.721 --> 33:36.640
I wonder where Miep is.
She's usually so prompt.

33:36.724 --> 33:39.226
[Siren Wailing]

33:46.859 --> 33:49.861
[Wailing Passes, Fades]

33:52.240 --> 33:55.742
â™ªâ™ª [Humming
"The Blue Danube"]

33:59.539 --> 34:01.748
Margot, come and dance
with me, please.

34:01.833 --> 34:04.751
I've got more work to do,
Anne.

34:06.170 --> 34:09.089
You know,
we're going to forget
how to dance.

34:09.172 --> 34:11.842
When we get out,
we won't remember a thing.

34:12.844 --> 34:15.846
â™ªâ™ª [Continues Humming]

34:17.139 --> 34:19.141
â™ªâ™ª [Joins In]

34:21.310 --> 34:24.228
â™ªâ™ª [Mr. Frank Singing
In German]

34:24.313 --> 34:26.815
[Toilet Flushing]

34:29.277 --> 34:31.445
â™ªâ™ª [Ends]

34:34.949 --> 34:36.867
Where's Peter?

34:36.951 --> 34:39.286
Where would he be?
With his cat.

34:39.370 --> 34:41.871
He hasn't finished
his lessons, has he?

34:42.873 --> 34:44.791
Peter.

34:44.876 --> 34:48.043
- Peter!
- What is it?

34:48.129 --> 34:50.839
Your mother says
to come out!

34:50.922 --> 34:53.842
I'm giving Mouschi
his dinner.
I'm feeding my cat.

34:53.926 --> 34:57.179
You know what your father says
about you wasting
all your time with that cat.

34:57.263 --> 35:01.141
I haven't even looked
at him since lunch.
I'm only telling you.

35:03.060 --> 35:04.978
I'll feed him.

35:05.062 --> 35:08.440
You stay out of here.
And I mean out.

35:08.524 --> 35:12.652
Is that any way for you
to talk to your little girlfriend?

35:14.238 --> 35:16.156
Mother,

35:16.240 --> 35:19.034
I asked you,
would you please not say that?

35:19.118 --> 35:21.203
Look, he's blushing.

35:21.287 --> 35:22.996
[Giggling]
He's blushing.

35:23.080 --> 35:26.792
Please. I'm not, but-
Leave me alone, will you.

35:26.876 --> 35:29.544
What did I say?
You act like it's something
to be ashamed of.

35:29.629 --> 35:32.547
It's nothing
to be ashamed of to have
a little girlfriend.

35:32.632 --> 35:35.759
- That's crazy. She's only 13.
- So what? And you're 16. It's just perfect.

35:35.885 --> 35:38.720
[Meowing]
Your father is 10 years
older than I am.

35:38.805 --> 35:42.974
Mr. Frank, I warn you,
this war lasts much longer,
we're gonna be related.

35:43.059 --> 35:44.726
Mazel tov.

35:44.811 --> 35:48.021
I haven't seen my cat
since lunch.

35:48.105 --> 35:50.106
I'm giving Mouschi
his dinner.

35:50.191 --> 35:52.359
My little Mouschi.

35:52.443 --> 35:55.362
I couldn't live
without my precious Mouschi.

35:55.446 --> 35:58.240
You wonderful cat,
you!

35:59.575 --> 36:01.451
All right,
Miss Quack-Quack.

36:01.577 --> 36:04.162
What's that?
Miss Quack-Quack!

36:04.247 --> 36:07.457
Heard all about you.
How you talk so much in class,
they call you Miss Quack-Quack.

36:07.583 --> 36:10.877
You're the most intolerable,
insufferable boy I ever met!
Quack-quack-quack!

36:12.296 --> 36:14.339
I'll give it to you
good!
Quack!

36:14.423 --> 36:16.341
- Ooh!
- [Door Slams]

36:16.425 --> 36:19.219
Anne dear,
you're hot.

36:19.303 --> 36:21.513
You're warm.
Are you feeling all right?

36:21.639 --> 36:24.558
Mother, please.
You don't have a fever,
do you?

36:24.642 --> 36:27.561
No.
You know we can't call
a doctor here, ever.

36:27.645 --> 36:30.564
There's only one thing to do:
watch carefully.

36:30.648 --> 36:34.234
Prevent an illness
before it comes.
Let me see your tongue.

36:34.318 --> 36:36.736
Mother, this is
perfectly absurd.

36:36.821 --> 36:39.155
Anne dear,
don't be such a baby.

36:39.282 --> 36:42.701
Let me see
your tongue.
[Toilet Flushes]

36:42.785 --> 36:44.661
Otto.
Anne.

36:44.787 --> 36:47.998
You hear your mother,
don't you?
Come on, open up.

36:50.126 --> 36:51.835
Quack.

36:51.919 --> 36:53.837
[Stomps Foot]

36:53.921 --> 36:55.839
Anne.

36:55.923 --> 36:57.924
Otto.
Anne.

37:09.729 --> 37:11.730
You're all right.

37:14.692 --> 37:17.777
[Siren Wailing]

37:19.655 --> 37:24.200
I think there's nothing
the matter with our Anne
that a ride on her bike...

37:24.285 --> 37:27.829
or a visit with
her friend Sanne de Vries
wouldn't cure.

37:27.914 --> 37:29.831
Isn't that so, Annele?

37:29.916 --> 37:31.917
[Siren Continues
Wailing]

37:35.254 --> 37:38.173
[Anne Narrating]
I keep wishing
that Peter was a girl...

37:38.257 --> 37:40.175
instead of a boy.

37:40.259 --> 37:43.261
Then I'd have someone
to talk to.

37:52.563 --> 37:54.981
With all the boys
in the world,

37:55.066 --> 37:58.068
why did I have to get
locked up with him?

37:59.612 --> 38:03.114
[Explosions]

38:13.209 --> 38:15.126
Is it someone?

38:15.211 --> 38:17.212
Is it Miep?

38:22.718 --> 38:24.636
It's strange
we don't hear.

38:24.720 --> 38:26.638
Maybe she got hurt-
the flak.

38:26.722 --> 38:29.641
She'll come.
I wish
she'd get here.

38:29.725 --> 38:31.726
I'm going crazy
without cigarettes.

38:35.731 --> 38:38.608
Anne, you got an "excellent"
in your history paper today...

38:38.693 --> 38:40.610
and a "very good"
in Latin.

38:40.695 --> 38:42.612
Yes, but how about
algebra?

38:42.697 --> 38:44.614
Well, I have
a confession to make.

38:44.699 --> 38:47.617
Up until now I managed
to stay ahead of you
in algebra.

38:47.702 --> 38:49.619
Today you caught up
with me.

38:49.704 --> 38:52.122
We'll leave it to Margot
to correct.

38:52.206 --> 38:54.791
Isn't algebra vile,
Father?
Vile.

38:54.875 --> 38:56.751
How did I do?

38:56.877 --> 38:59.129
Excellent,
of course.
Anne, Anne, please.

38:59.213 --> 39:02.465
Your French composition today
was wonderful, just wonderful.

39:02.550 --> 39:04.968
Mrs. Van Daan,
may I try it on?

39:05.052 --> 39:06.970
No, Anne.

39:07.054 --> 39:09.139
It's all right.
Really.

39:09.223 --> 39:12.142
But please,
be careful with it.

39:12.226 --> 39:16.146
My father gave me this coat
the year before he died.

39:16.230 --> 39:19.399
He always bought me
the best money could buy.

39:52.391 --> 39:55.310
Mrs. Van Daan, did you have
a lot of boyfriends...

39:55.394 --> 39:57.312
before you
were married?

39:57.396 --> 39:59.314
Anne, that's
a personal question.

39:59.398 --> 40:02.317
It's not courteous
to ask personal questions.

40:02.401 --> 40:04.319
I don't mind.

40:04.403 --> 40:07.572
Anneke, our house
was always swarming
with boys.

40:07.656 --> 40:11.284
- When I was a young girl-
- Oh, no. Not again.

40:11.368 --> 40:13.828
Shut up!

40:15.915 --> 40:19.250
[Mrs., Mr. Van Daan]
One summer we had a big house
in Hilversum.

40:19.335 --> 40:22.170
[Mr. Van Daan Continues]
The boys-

40:25.841 --> 40:30.095
The boys would come
buzzing around like bees
around a jam pot.

40:30.179 --> 40:32.097
When I was 17-

40:32.181 --> 40:35.100
Well, we were wearing
our skirts very short
in those days,

40:35.184 --> 40:37.435
and I had
such good-looking legs.

40:37.520 --> 40:42.023
I still have. I may not be
as pretty as I used to be,
but I still have my legs.

40:42.108 --> 40:44.025
How about it,
Mr. Frank?

40:44.110 --> 40:48.196
All right,
all right.
We see them.

40:48.280 --> 40:51.241
I'm not asking you.
I'm asking Mr. Frank.

40:51.325 --> 40:52.992
Mother,
for heaven's sakes.

40:53.077 --> 40:54.994
Oh, I embarrass you too,
do I?

40:55.079 --> 40:59.124
Well, I only hope
the girl you marry
has as good.

40:59.208 --> 41:03.711
Anneke, my father
used to worry about me with
all the boys hanging around.

41:03.796 --> 41:06.714
And he used to say to me,
"If any of those boys
get fresh,

41:06.799 --> 41:08.716
"you just say to him,

41:08.801 --> 41:12.762
'Remember, Mr. So-and-so,
remember, I am a lady."'

41:12.847 --> 41:15.223
Look at you,
talking that way
in front of her.

41:15.349 --> 41:18.518
Don't you know she puts it
all down in that damned diary?
So what if she does?

41:18.602 --> 41:20.728
I'm only telling
the truth.

41:22.815 --> 41:24.732
Haven't you
finished yet?

41:24.817 --> 41:26.985
No.

41:27.069 --> 41:28.778
Oh. The thinker.

41:28.863 --> 41:30.780
Leave him alone.

41:30.865 --> 41:33.825
All right, all right.
I'm a dunce, a hopeless case.

41:33.909 --> 41:35.827
[Mrs. Van Daan]
You're not hopeless.

41:35.911 --> 41:39.706
It's just that you haven't
got anyone to help you
like Father helps Anne and me.

41:39.790 --> 41:43.668
Well, if I-
Well, if we could help-

41:43.752 --> 41:46.171
What about it, Peter?
Would you like to study with us?

41:46.255 --> 41:49.007
Shall we make
our school coeducational?

41:49.091 --> 41:51.593
Thanks. Yes.

41:51.677 --> 41:55.263
Mr. Frank, you are an angel,
an absolute angel.

41:55.347 --> 41:58.683
Why didn't I meet you
before I met that one there?

42:00.686 --> 42:02.604
I... think
it might be better...

42:02.688 --> 42:05.106
if you went
into your room,
Peter, to work.

42:05.191 --> 42:07.108
Excuse me.

42:07.193 --> 42:11.571
You listen to Mr. Frank.
Mr. Frank is
a highly educated man.

42:14.450 --> 42:17.035
[Mr. Van Daan]
It's after 8:00.
Where are they?

42:17.161 --> 42:20.788
At least one of them
should have come.
They'll come. Don't worry.

42:20.873 --> 42:23.791
Don't tell me.
I know something's wrong.

42:23.876 --> 42:27.253
Isn't it bad enough around here
without you sprawling
all over the place?

42:27.338 --> 42:30.215
If you didn't smoke
all the time, you wouldn't
be so bad-tempered.

42:30.341 --> 42:33.760
Do you see me smoking?
Oh, you already smoked up
all the cigarettes?

42:33.844 --> 42:36.763
One package.
Miep only brought me
one package.

42:36.847 --> 42:39.641
It's a filthy habit,
and this is a good time
to break yourself of it.

42:39.725 --> 42:42.644
- Oh, stop it.
- You're smoking up
all our money!

42:42.728 --> 42:45.104
Will you shut up!

42:48.651 --> 42:50.652
And what are you
staring at?

42:51.946 --> 42:54.739
I never heard grown-ups
quarrel like that before.

42:54.823 --> 42:56.741
I thought
only children quarreled.

42:56.825 --> 42:59.786
This isn't a quarrel.
It's a discussion.

42:59.870 --> 43:03.122
- And I never heard children
so rude before.
- I, rude?

43:03.207 --> 43:05.124
Yes!
Anne,
drink your milk.

43:05.209 --> 43:09.087
The trouble with you is,
you've been spoiled.
You need a spanking.

43:09.171 --> 43:12.090
Remember, Mr. So-and-so,
that I am a lady.

43:12.174 --> 43:15.093
Mmm, you're
the most aggravating-

43:15.177 --> 43:18.096
Why aren't you nice and quiet
like your sister Margot?

43:18.180 --> 43:20.598
Why do you
have to show off
all the time?

43:20.683 --> 43:24.102
Let me give you
a little advice, young lady-
men don't like that in a girl.

43:24.186 --> 43:27.563
Do you know that?
A man likes a girl who will
listen to him once in a while.

43:27.690 --> 43:31.609
A domestic girl
who loves to cook and clean-
I'd cut my throat first!

43:31.694 --> 43:33.945
I'd open my veins.

43:34.029 --> 43:36.322
I'm going to be
remarkable.

43:36.448 --> 43:40.493
I'm going to Paris
to study music and art.
Paris? Yeah, yeah.

43:40.577 --> 43:44.747
I'm going to be an actress,
or a writer, or a dancer.

43:44.832 --> 43:46.833
[Mrs. Van Daan Gasps]

43:46.959 --> 43:48.876
Look what you did.
I'm so sorry.

43:48.961 --> 43:51.337
You clumsy little fool!

43:51.463 --> 43:54.382
This is the coat
my father gave me!
I'm so sorry.

43:54.466 --> 43:57.385
You ruined it.
What do you care?
Ruined it!

43:57.469 --> 44:00.388
[Sobbing]
I could kill you!
I could just kill you!

44:00.472 --> 44:03.891
Petronella.
Liebchen, Liebchen.
[Continues Sobbing]

44:03.976 --> 44:05.893
Petronella.

44:05.978 --> 44:07.895
[Mr. Van Daan]
It's only a coat.

44:07.980 --> 44:10.898
Anne, you must not
behave in that way.

44:10.983 --> 44:14.193
It was an accident.
Anyone can have an accident.

44:14.278 --> 44:17.196
I don't mean that.
I mean the answering back.

44:17.281 --> 44:19.198
You must not
answer back.

44:19.283 --> 44:21.200
They're
our guests.

44:21.285 --> 44:24.537
You don't hear Margot
getting into any arguments
with them, do you?

44:24.621 --> 44:27.040
Try to be
like Margot.

44:27.124 --> 44:31.044
And have them
walk all over me the way
they do her? No, thanks.

44:31.128 --> 44:34.047
I don't know what
happens to you, Anne.

44:34.131 --> 44:37.258
If I had ever
talked to my mother
as you talk to me-

44:37.343 --> 44:39.177
Things have changed,
Mother.

44:39.261 --> 44:41.512
People aren't
like that anymore.

44:41.597 --> 44:45.516
"Yes, Mother." "No, Mother."
"Anything you say, Mother."

44:45.601 --> 44:48.061
I've got to
fight things out
for myself.

44:48.145 --> 44:50.063
But-
Make something
of myself.

44:50.147 --> 44:53.066
It isn't necessary
to fight to do it.
Margot doesn't fight.

44:53.150 --> 44:55.068
Margot!
That's all I hear.

44:55.152 --> 44:57.070
"Why aren't you like Margot?"

44:57.154 --> 45:00.573
Everything she does is right,
and everything I do is wrong!

45:00.657 --> 45:04.494
You're all against me,
and you worst of all!

45:05.788 --> 45:08.206
[Sighs]
[Door Slams]

45:08.290 --> 45:11.209
I don't know how
we can go on living this way.

45:11.293 --> 45:14.545
I can't say a word to Anne,
she flies at me.

45:14.630 --> 45:18.549
You know Anne.
In a half hour she'll be out here
laughing and joking.

45:18.634 --> 45:20.885
And, uh-

45:20.969 --> 45:23.888
I told your father it wouldn't work-
two families.

45:23.972 --> 45:26.891
But no, no,
he had to ask them.

45:26.975 --> 45:28.893
[Footsteps, Faint]

45:28.977 --> 45:30.978
Shh.

45:35.943 --> 45:37.360
[Footsteps Approaching,
Growing Louder]

45:37.361 --> 45:39.862
[Footsteps Approaching,
Growing Louder]

45:44.535 --> 45:46.452
[Knocking]

45:46.537 --> 45:48.454
[Sighs]

45:48.539 --> 45:51.457
Every time
I hear that sound,
my heart stops.

45:51.542 --> 45:53.543
It's Miep.
Father!

45:54.962 --> 45:56.963
Yes?
It's Miep.

46:00.759 --> 46:03.136
Here's your list.

46:03.262 --> 46:05.179
Is it Miep?
Yes.

46:05.264 --> 46:07.181
At last I'll have
some cigarettes.

46:07.266 --> 46:09.183
Miep's here.

46:09.268 --> 46:12.687
I can't tell you
how sorry I am
about the coat.

46:12.771 --> 46:14.647
Don't worry.

46:14.773 --> 46:16.691
Hello, hello.
Miep.

46:16.775 --> 46:18.693
Mr. Kraler!

46:18.777 --> 46:21.654
When Mr. Kraler comes,
the sun begins to shine.

46:21.780 --> 46:24.699
Dirk has had
to leave.
Dirk is Miep's fiancÃ©.

46:24.783 --> 46:28.202
He had to go into hiding
in the country
to escape a labor call-up.

46:28.287 --> 46:31.205
But he has let me
have the radio for you.

46:31.290 --> 46:33.207
He shouldn't have.

46:33.292 --> 46:35.209
Oh, it was
too dangerous.

46:35.294 --> 46:37.211
Look!

46:37.296 --> 46:39.213
[Gasps]

